AGI - Goodbye to James Harrison, known as "the man from the golden arm", the Australian who saved more than two million > of children during his almost nine decades of life continually giving his blood, which contained a precious antibody to fight a rare disease. >
The Australian, donated about 1,170 times its plasma, died at the age of 88 in mid-February in a nursing home, said Saturday the Australian Red Cross.&nbsp;
Harrison's determination to share his precious blood dates back to the age of 14, when he was subjected to surgery on his lungs and received numerous plasma transfusions.&nbsp; Harrison's blood, which has never lost an appointment to donate it, contained anti-D, an antibody that protects fetuses from a deadly blood disease > called neonate hemolytic disease (HDNB).
Harrison's plasma was used to create vaccines against RHND, > a blood disease> in which a pregnant mother produces antibodies passing through the placenta and reach the red blood cells of the fetus, sometimes causing death.
“He was very proud to have saved so many lives, at no cost or pain (...) He always said it doesn’t hurt and that the life you save might be yours,” said his daughter Trecey Mellowhip in the announcement of death, spread on Saturday. The same Trecey and two Harrison pronipots are among the more than 2 million children who received the vaccine.&nbsp;
“As an anti-D beneficiary, > left a family that could not exist without its valuable donations... It made him happy to know that there were many families like ours who had survived thanks to his generosity," said the daughter.
Stephen Cornelissen, director of the blood collection department of the Australian Red Cross, described Harrison as "a generous man who dedicated his entire life to donation".
